\f0\fs32 \cf0 \strokec2 That should be sufficient to deal with the frustration. But really I should clarify that it\'92s not you I\'92m frustrated with, but myself, or perhaps the idea of you which has persisted inside my head. I resent what you have become to me, through no fault of your own and entirely through my own. I\'92m\'85 sorry.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Now on to the next emotion\'97 or perhaps category is a better word. Speaking of better words: fixation. That is what you are, the next victim of my attentions and affections and fixations; I imagine it is not a pleasant thing to be. And yet I counteract my thoughts of you with thoughts of prior fixations so this must be what you are. You occupy too much of my focus; even my lungs and chest tense at your every action, you have brought back symptoms I did not know I could feel anymore.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf0 \strokec2 And I\'92m playing a losing hand, I\'92m not so silly that I can\'92t tell how one-sided this is. Damn it all, I think I might love you and I really don\'92t want to. I\'92ve got no fancy words or beautiful prose for you now. There is nothing good about this.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf0 \strokec2 From you perhaps I have learned my definition of love; or rather I have learned that love and fixation were always the same. That love requires something like fascination and care. I think I may never be happy in this regard, but no matter.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 This is a letter I hope I never send you, in part because it is poor prose on my part, and in part because I will regret it. Instead I will spin a lie for you, and trust that you are clever enough to unravel it.
\f1\fs24 \
